  "prompt": "Is Sri Ramakrishna Paramahamsa an avatar?",
  "response": "The question of whether Sri Ramakrishna Paramahamsa is an avatar (a divine incarnation) is a matter of spiritual belief and interpretation, particularly within the Hindu tradition. Sri Ramakrishna (1836\u20131886) is widely revered as a mystic, saint, and spiritual teacher whose life and teachings have had a profound impact on Hinduism and beyond.\n\nIn Hinduism, an avatar is understood to be a deliberate descent of the Divine (usually Vishnu or another form of God) into the human realm for a specific purpose, such as restoring dharma (righteousness) or guiding humanity. While many followers of Sri Ramakrishna regard him as an incarnation of God or a divine being, this belief is not universally accepted and largely depends on individual faith and devotional outlook.\n\nSri Ramakrishna himself often spoke of God in a universal sense and emphasized the direct experience of the Divine as the ultimate goal of spiritual practice. He did not explicitly claim to be an avatar, but his profound spiritual experiences, accessibility to various states of consciousness, and ability to embody diverse spiritual paths (including Vedanta, Tantra, and devotion to deities like Kali) have led many to view him as a divine figure.\n\nHis chief disciple, **Swami Vivekananda**, and the monastic order he founded, the **Ramakrishna Mission**, have helped propagate his teachings without necessarily asserting that Sri Ramakrishna was an avatar. Instead, they focus on his universal message of harmony, devotion, and the realization of God.\n\nIn summary, whether Sri Ramakrishna is considered an avatar depends on one's spiritual perspective. While some Hindus and devotees see him as a divine incarnation, others revere him as an extraordinary saint and spiritual guide.",
